<TEXT>
jesse jackson said monday for the first time 
that he would accept the no 2 spot on the democratic ticket if it 
were offered to him 
jackson technically remained in contention for the democratic 
nomination even though michael dukakis has a numerical lock on a 
firstballot victory at the convention 
he has been saying for weeks that he ought to be offered the 
vice presidential nomination but up until monday jackson refused 
to say whether he would take dukakis up on such an offer 
he broke his silence amid indications that dukakis would 
announce his choice within a few days 
if it was offered to me i would accept it jackson told 
reporters after a meeting with paul brountas the dukakis aide who 
has been coordinating the search for a running mate 
jackson said he gave brountas the detailed personal financial 
information that has been solicited from prospective running mates 
and said he offered his candid view as to the office of vice 
presidentand what i thought my qualifications would be 
brountas refused to discuss the substance of the discussion 
saying only that it was an excellent meetingvery productive 
jackson said it is selfevident that he wants to be vice 
president and said he assured brountas that he would be a loyal 
second to dukakis 
however he said that if he is not chosen he would expect 
further discussions with dukakis about his role in the fall 
campaign 
jackson has indicated in recent weeks that his forces might 
stage floor fights over platform issues at the democratic national 
convention which opens next week 
but he said monday we intend to have an effective 
informative convention that would inspire our nation unify our 
party and take us to victory 
jackson said platform disagreements were not discussed in the 
meeting with brountas 
brountas returned to boston monday night and went to dukakis 
brookline home for a latenight meeting with the governor dukakis 
had met with brountas earlier in the day 
jackson has said he is the most qualified to share the ticket 
with dukakis and has called the others known to be under 
consideration unknown quantities 
they include sens john glenn of ohio albert gore jr of 
tennessee lloyd bentsen of texas and bob graham of florida and 
reps richard gephardt of missouri and lee hamilton of indiana 
jackson asked what he thought of the vice presidential 
selection process said i have no basis to challenge the 
integrity of mr brountas or gov dukakis 
he added if this is just a charade it is a great waste of 
their time at a time when time is precious 
jackson later flew to cincinnati for a fundraiser he was 
returning to washington on tuesday to address the naacp and hold 
meetings 
</TEXT>
