<TEXT>
the sandinista government on monday 
ordered us ambassador richard melton and seven other american 
embassy officials to leave the country within 72 hours accusing 
them of state terrorism 
it also closed the opposition newspaper la prensa for 15 days 
shut down the roman catholic radio station radio catolica and 
arrested an opposition leader 
us secretary of state george p shultz on tuesday called the 
expulsions order an absolute outrage he did not say what 
action he planned to take 
he spoke in manila while on an asian tour 
melton notified the state department at 7 pm that he and the 
seven staff members were given 72 hours to leave nicaragua said 
department press officer rudi boone in washington boone said the 
department was drafting a statement 
the developments came one day after police clashed with 
thousands of demonstrators at an antisandinista rally 
president daniel ortega on sunday described the demonstration as 
being part of a us plan to undermine his leftist government and 
vowed to act with force against violations of public order 
foreign minister miguel descoto announced the decision to expel 
the americans he said they were engaging in activities 
complementary to the state terrorism the administration of us 
president ronald reagan is carrying out against nicaragua 
descoto said he called melton to his office monday afternoon to 
advise him of the decision which declared the ambassador and the 
seven others unwelcome descoto also said he gave melton a sealed 
letter advising shultz of the expulsions 
speaking with reporters at a foreign ministry news conference 
descoto called melton a robot of the maniacal assistant 
secretary of state for interamerican affairs elliott abrams 
descotos letter identified the seven other us diplomats as 
john e hope first secretary in charge of economic and commercial 
affairs hugh v simon jr first secretary delvin junker and 
david nolan both second secretaries john s creamer and aubrey a 
carlson third secrtaries and vice consuls and robert bruce 
murray an assistant attache 
descoto said us embassy officials were at sundays opposition 
demonstration in nandaime about 40 miles south of managua 
melton he said came to nicaragua in his mind to fill a 
leadership vacuum in this country and he became confused 
the government earlier accused melton of carrying out a 
destabilization plan against nicaragua 
melton filled the post left vacant since july 1987 when 
ambassador harry bergold returned to washington 
it was believed to be the first time nicaragua had declared an 
american ambassador persona non grata 
on june 6 1983 the government expelled three us diplomats 
accused of taking part in an alleged plot to poison descoto the 
united states responded by closing several nicaraguan consulates in 
the united states 
melton presented his credentials here in may when he arrived in 
nicaragua april 12 melton 52 said it was a decisive moment in 
usnicaraguan relations 
la prensa the only opposition daily in nicaragua reopened oct 
1 1987 after being shut down by the government for more than a 
year 
the government allowed la prensa to reopen as part of its 
efforts to comply with a regional peace plan that ortega and the 
four other central american presidents signed in august 1987 radio 
catolica shut down in jan 1 1986 for failing to broadcast 
ortegas yearend message to the nation also was allowed to reopen 
last october 
in closing radio catolica the interior ministry accused the 
station of inciting to violence disorder and lack of respect for 
constitutional government 
monsignor bismarck carballo the stations director called the 
order unjust and arbitrary 
an official in the interior ministry press office speaking on 
condition of anonymity said police arrested secretarygeneral 
miriam arguello of the conservative party for being the principal 
instigator of yesterdays events in nandaime 
pedro joaquin chamorro a director of the usbacked rebels 
known as contras said in miami earlier monday the sandinistas 
are demonstrating once again that they are not prepared for 
democracy 
chamorro said the contras have been negotiating in good faith 
with the sandinistas but that continued repression inside 
nicaragua would leave them little choice but to return to armed 
struggle 
police arrested 42 people including carballos brother in 
breaking up sundays antigovernment protest an interior 
department statement said monday the march had been authorized by 
sandinista officials beforehand 
police said 10 officers were hurt and that protesters threw 
rocks at police which responded with tear gas 
witnesses said police started the fracas 
the sandinistas came to power in a popular revolution in july 
1979 that ended 42 years of rule by the rightist proamerican 
somoza dynasty 
the us government backed trained and supplied the contras 
since 1981 in their fight against the sandinistas 
this is to show the people want democracy ms arguello said 
before the fighting broke out later a civilian struck her with a 
large club as a group of police applauded 
the march was held to protest government economic policies 
the sandinistas have been losing popularity because of the 
shattered economy and the ongoing war 
</TEXT>
