<TEXT>
roses not derricks bedeck the 
streets of this capital of north sea oil and the tough scots who 
live here are proud of that 
oil changed many lives made some people rich and pushed out 
the ailing fishing industry but it has not spoiled the city 
sandwiched betweeen the rivers don and dee or changed aberdonians 
they say 
aberdeen lives with oil not for it and felt largely unscathed 
by the two decades of vast changes it brought at least until last 
weeks oil rig tragedy claimed 166 lives including many 
abderdonians 
aberdeen doesnt see itself as an oil town says the rev 
james stewart of the kirk church of st nicholas the seat of the 
citys ancient church of scotland congregation its a town on 
which oil has made a deep impact but it has sufficiently deep 
roots in the past and in the hinterland to see itself as something 
more 
the city of 214000 residents stresses this in a brochure for 
tourists since the discovery of north sea oil aberdeen has 
justifiably earned the title of europes offshore oil capital 
the city however has not been spoiled by this new industry 
only occasionally can an oil rig be seen far out on the horizon 
under tow to a new location or at anchor waiting a new contract 
stewarts stone church looms over a city built of granite from 
rowhouses to two early 16th century universities splashes of color 
come only from miles of roses lining the streets for aberdeens 
11th attempt to win the britain in bloom competition 
aberdeen is a tough nofrills city 
its a town where the character of the people in some ways is 
a reflection of the stone of which the city is built says 
stewart a scotsman who arrived in the city a few years after the 
oil boom began in the early 70s 
granite is a very hard stone and theres a kind of 
independent toughness about the aberdonians its not a city which 
wears its heart on its sleeve 
in the days after wednesdays oil rig disaster that seemed true 
memorial services were held and some flags flew at halfstaff 
but shoppers thronged the main street as crying seagulls drifted 
overhead 
the city mourned but privately 
were a closeknit people said kathleen skene head 
bartender at the aberdeen petroleum club once the elite haven of 
north sea pioneers oilwise americans and since the world oil 
slump a haunt of fish merchants and businessmen 
most people know someone or know of someone whos been lost 
it certainly affected a lot of lives she said 
once aberdeen folk were considered lucky to have oil on their 
doorstep said the sunday post newspaper which calls itself 
scotlands largest sunday paper now like many mining communities 
before them they have found the earth doesnt give up its riches 
without a price 
the first north sea oil was struck in 1969 and brought to shore 
in 1975 at the time aberdeen was in decline 
but from 1970 to 1984 jobs rose by 54 percent house prices 
rose nearly 20 percent a year and annual passengers through 
aberdeen airport rose 1370 percent to more than a million the 
city says 
with oil came a lot of outsiders what the aberdonians call 
inabootcomers in their dialect especially from the united 
states 
i think when oil first started we definitely resented the 
americans because they had the good jobs they made the money and 
a lot of aberdonians didnt benefit said ms skene not 
everyone made money 
others welcomed oil from the start 
it meant a complete turnaround from fishing to the oil 
scene said manager frank naughton of north star fishing co a 
major fishing fleet now used mostly as oil support boats with 
the decline in fishing personally id say it was a good thing oil 
came in 
since the world oil slump many americans have gone and the jobs 
are not as well paid but the city still thrives and until last 
week had settled quietly into oil work 
still the rev stewart believes aberdeens granite spirit will 
help it face up to the disaster 
its sobering but i think its part of the character of the 
people here to pick up the threads and make the best of it 
</TEXT>
