<TEXT>
a legislative body of the episcopal church passed 
an proposal sunday on the ordination of homosexuals that left both 
proponents and opponents saying they had prevailed 
the house of deputies one of the churchs two governing bodies 
passed an amendment during the churchs 69th general convention 
that states no one shall be denied access to the selection 
process for ordination except provided by canons of this church 
in order to become part of the churchs canon law the deputies 
amendment would have to be adopted by the house of bishops the 
churchs other governing body before the convention comes to an 
end monday 
currently official church canon law contains no provisions 
barring homosexuals from being ordained but a 1979 resolution 
opposes ordination 
church spokesman richard henshaw said sundays vote was 
confusing 
this may be one of those rare moments when both sides think 
they have a victory he said 
opponents to the ordination of practicing homosexual priests say 
the deputies amendment reaffirms a 1979 church resolution that 
said we believe it is not appropriate for this church to ordain 
a practicing homosexual 
the church is clear on its position that it will not ordain 
homosexuals there is a difference between orientation and 
behavior no one has the right to ordination said dean james r 
gundrum of south dakota 
