us officials expressed optimism for 
prospects of peace in angola as south africa angola cuba and the 
united states opened talks today aimed at ending the longrunning 
conflict 
the officials met at the us coast guard base on governors 
island in new york harbor for talks that are expected to end late 
tuesday or early wednesday said anne stoddard a spokeswoman for 
the us mission to the united nations 
us officials in washington said there were some hopeful signs 
on a timetable for a cuban troop withdrawal from angola as part of 
a peace settlement a peace settlement may also be linked to black 
majority rule in namibia 
one indication is that the soviet union which has provided 
angolas marxist government with billions of dollars in military 
equipment since 1975 has shown interest in ending the conflict 
there through a negotiated settlement said the officials who 
spoke on condition of anonymity 
they also say angola for the first time has accepted the 
principle of a total cuban troop withdrawal 
but cuba has steadily increased its troop commitment to angola 
in the past six months close to 50000 cubans are believed to be 
stationed there compared with 35000 to 37000 last fall the 
officials said 
according to the us officials cuba probably has increased its 
troop deployment to strengthen its bargaining position for the 
negotiations 
the us goal is to achieve a timetable for a full cuban troop 
withdrawal that would take place simultaneously with implementation 
of a united nations security council resolution calling for 
independence in neighboring namibia which has been administered by 
south africa for 70 years 
angola and cuba thus far have said the cuban withdrawal should 
take place over four years while the namibian independence process 
should be consistent with the oneyear timetable specified in the 
un resolution 
but the reagan administration sees the fouryear proposal for 
the cuban withdrawal as an opening bargaining position that is 
subject to change as peace talks proceed disagreement over a 
timetable for a cuban pullback is probably the most difficult 
unresolved issue 
the four parties first met in london in early may and then 
reconvened late last month in cairo egypt in cairo the parties 
agreed that a statement of principles governing future negotiations 
would be useful 
the us delegation will be led by assistant secretary of state 
chester crocker who heads the african affairs bureau and has been 
working on a southern africa peace settlement since he joined the 
administration in 1981 
the angola civil war and the struggle for independence in 
namibia are among the oldest armed conflicts in the world 
the united states is a party to the angolan conflict because it 
has been supporting an anticommunist guerrilla movement since 
1985 but the administration does not regard this involvement as an 
appropriate item for the ongoing negotiations because it believes 
the talks should focus on the withdrawal of foreign forces from 
that country 
south africa has repeatedly sent troops across the border into 
angola in support of the usbacked rebel forces there angolas 
government wants the permanent withdrawal of all south african 
forces from angola 
shortly after the cairo talks ended in late june south african 
troops clashed with cuban and angolan forces in southwest angola 
near the namibian border 
