the states method of electing state 
district judges was challenged today in a federal lawsuit that 
charges the atlarge system makes it more difficult for 
mexicanamericans and blacks to be elected 
the suit filed in us district court in midland by three 
groups on behalf of the league of united latin american citizens 
and local citizens focuses on approximately 20 counties said 
rolando l rios an attorney 
if judges are to be elected then all members of the 
electorate should have a fair and equal chance to elect judges of 
their choice said domingo garcia chairman of the texas rural 
legal foundation 
the foundation was joined by the southwest voter registration 
education project and texas rural legal aid in filing the suit 
counties named as examples in the lawsuit included harris 
dallas ector mcclennan tarrant midland travis jefferson 
galveston lubbock fort bend smith brazos brazoria taylor 
wichita angelina gregg and bell 
according to the suit those counties contain 190 state judicial 
districts and a combined minority population of nearly 30 percent 
but only 10 of the judges 53 percent are minorities 
the number of minority judges sitting in those counties is 
minuscule said william l garrent a dallas lawyer 
in the atlarge system all the judges in a county are elected 
by the voters of the whole county if a county is mostly white 
that makes it more difficult for a minority candidate to win 
if the county is divided into districts its more likely that 
minorities will make up a majority in at least one of the districts 
the lawyers said many texas counties have only a single state 
district judge and so were not named 
rios said that if the lawsuit is successful and singlemember 
districts are created the number of minority judges in the 
counties could increase from fewer than 20 to more than 110 
