<TEXT>
a booster rocket that was to be tested in two 
weeks in utah was damaged when a workman incorrectly installed a 
test gauge but nasa said today that the accident is not expected 
to delay the resumption of space shuttle flights 
the space shuttle discovery is poised on its launching pad at 
cape canaveral fla for liftoff on sept 4 the successful 
outcome of the booster rocket test in utah is a requirement for the 
launching to take place 
nasa spokesman david garrett said the test motor will have to be 
disassembled as far as the center field joint for evaluation and 
possible repairs and then be reassembled 
that he said will reuire rescheduling of the test from july 25 
to at least midaugust but he added we do not expect it 
will affect the sts 26 launch schedule 
sts26 is the official designation for the first flight of a 
space shuttle since a 1968 explosion destroyed challenger and 
killed seven crew members 
edward s campion a national aeronautics and space 
administration spokesman said a morton thiokol worker damaged the 
test rocket over the weekend while attempting to install a gauge 
that was to be used during a test firing 
it the gauge was installed with an incorrect setting which 
caused the hardware to be damaged said campion 
ed medal a spokesman for nasas marshall space flight center in 
huntsville ala said the rockets center field joint was 
inadvertantly overpressurized during leak checks 
he said one section of the joint was subjected to pressure of 
1000 pounds per square inch another section he said was to have 
been checked at 100 psi but was mistakenly subjected to the higher 
pressure 
the rocket engine was to be test fired in utah on july 25 
campion said nasa officials have said that that test must be 
successfully completed before the space shuttle can fly again 
space shuttle discovery is now on a launch pad at the kennedy space 
center in florida and is scheduled to be launched early in 
september 
campion said officials are trying to determine how long the test 
firing in utah will be delayed by the needed repairs and if this 
delay will affect the space shuttle launch 
the test rocket in utah incorporates a new booster design 
created after the january 1986 challenger accident which killed 
seven astronauts space shuttle challenger exploded after its 
launch from the kennedy space center the explosion was blamed on a 
flawed rocket booster design the space shuttle fleet has been 
grounded while the booster had been redesigned and tested 
nasa officials said the july 25 test was crucial for clearing 
the shuttle for the resumption of space flights 
