the senate approved on a voice vote monday 
legislation which authorizes catholic universities in the city to 
deny equal treatment to homosexual student organizations 
the measure was sponsored by sen william armstrong rcolo 
and passed as an amendment to the district of columbias 32 
billion budget bill armstrong argued that church institutions as 
a matter of religious liberty have the right to exclude gay groups 
from student organizations accorded campus resources 
sen lowell weicker rconn argued the amendment would codify 
discrimination the subject matter before us is outrageous 
weicker charged it is just good oldfashioned straightforward 
bigotry this thing should go back down the sewer from which it 
came 
armstrong denied that his proposal was antihomosexual and said 
it was designed to correct a problem which arose for georgetown 
university when a dc appellate court ruled that the school had 
violated the citys human rights code by denying equal treatment to 
gay organizations 
in the wake of that ruling georgetown agreed in march to 
provide meeting space a mailbox and the right to apply for 
student government funding to two gay student groups but the 
school was not required under the settlement to officially 
recognize the student groups university leaders said official 
recognition would violate church teachings 
georgetown did not encourage armstrong to propose his amendment 
and has no intention of reversing the march agreement or denying 
similar access to gay groups in the future according to betsy 
whittleder a school spokeswoman 
the city budget bill was approved by the senate on a 6429 vote 
but now must go to a housesenate conference committee to work out 
differences between the two chambers 
