<TEXT>
a federal judge monday struck down a georgia law 
requiring minors to tell their parents before getting an abortion 
the second time in as many years the law has failed to pass 
constitutional muster 
us district judge robert hall granted a preliminary injunction 
sought by planned parenthood to stop implementation of the parental 
notification act 
the law which requires girls under 18 to notify their parents 
before getting an abortion was to have taken effect july 1 hall 
had blocked its implementation pending his ruling 
hall voided a similar but more stringent statute last year after 
the atlanta and augusta chapters of planned parenthood challenged 
it saying it placed too great a burden on teenage girls 
the law was rewritten to ease some requirements during the 1988 
general assembly but the two planned parenthood chapters and 
atlanta physician orrin moore who performs abortions again 
challenged it on virtually the same grounds their suit was filed 
on behalf of more than 4000 teenage girls who received abortions 
in 1985 
under the rewritten law teenage girls in some cases would have 
had to wait 24 hours after notifying their parents for the abortion 
to be performed the lawsuit challenged that section and also said 
the act failed to guarantee anonymity to some girls 
the suit also challenged a provision of the law that allows a 
girl to go to juvenile court to obtain a waiver if she does not 
wish to notify her parents the suit said the time involved in 
getting such a waiver sometimes three weeks or more is too long 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

