the reagan administration said monday that 
us participation in a centuryold international accord could help 
trim americas 2 billion annual loss to film and recording pirates 
assistant secretary of state eugene mcallister appeared before 
the senate foreign relations committee to argue for us membership 
in the berne convention for the protection of literary and artistic 
works created in 1886 
today we are experiencing a technolgical revolution involving 
such innovations as computers communications satellites optical 
discs and many more mcallister noted many international 
copyright experts here and abroad believe that the berne convention 
is a comprehensive and dynamic instrument which meets the 
challenges brought on by the new technologioes 
mcallister said the berne convention could protect us 
copyrights in 79 countries 24 of which do not belong to the 
universal copyright convention the united states is already a 
member of that accord 
copyright official ralph oman testified that us 
representatives recently visited turkey and egypt with complaints 
of pirating but were told that since the united states did not 
belong to the berne convention us rights were not legally 
protected in those countries 
other countries on the list of 24 are mainly african including 
south africa romania thailand and uruguay are also among them 
oman said the list covers minor markets but major pirates 
he did not further identify any of the pirating countries 
he noted the spread of us popular culture all over the world 
for the first time us films and recorded music now make more 
money abroad than in the united states he said 
the house already has approved the bill for us membership 
which now awaits action by the senate 
