<TEXT>
air safety authorities on monday urged that 
the federal requirements for brake wear on large jetliners be 
tightened to avoid future accidents such as one involving an 
american airlines dc10 last may at the dallasfort worth airport 
the national transportation safety board said that eight of the 
10 brakes on the american dc10 failed when the pilot aborted his 
takeoff after getting indications that the planes flaps or slats 
might not have been in the proper position 
the jetliner with 240 passengers aboard skidded 1000 feet 
beyond the end of the runway injuring the three cockpit crew 
members and five passengers and extensively damaging the aircraft 
the federal aviation administration responding to the ntsb 
findings said it agreed with the boards conclusions and is in the 
process of developing new minimum requirements for brake wear for 
all jetliners and possibly special directives for the dc10 
we have been following the matter of revised minimum brake 
standards for jetliners closely since the accident at dallasfort 
worth said an faa statement faa spokesman fred farrar said the 
review is still in the early stages and no time frame for 
implementing new requirements has been established 
the pilot of the american dc10 chose to abort his takeoff from 
dallasfort worth on may 21 after an instrument indicated that the 
planes flaps or slats which help the jet gain lift were not in 
proper position 
a later examination showed they were in a position for takeoff 
but that the warning signal was activated because of a slight 
outof tolerance condition involving one of the slats the ntsb 
urged that the warning system be redesigned 
when the takeoff was aborted the plane slowed as it should have 
from 204 mph to 149 mph during the first six seconds but the 
safety board said at that point the deceleration decayed 
rapidly the jetliner left the runway traveling 117 mph lost its 
nose gear and plowed through the dirt for 1000 feet before coming 
to a halt 
eight of the planes 10 wheel brakes were near the maximum 
wear limits before the aborted takeoff and failed within 8 or 9 
seconds after being applied the investigators said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

