<TEXT>
as china rushes into economic and social change 
its university students are coming under increasing stress and 
pressure to achieve officials have begun to offer them 
psychological counseling 
competition of course brings more stress to students said 
chen chongkeng director of the clinical psychology section of 
beijing universitys psychology department 
at one time under the chinese communist system students were 
assured of a plum job after graduation but todays students are 
told to start looking for employment on their own and many find 
the competition tough 
a college education also used to be free with the state picking 
up the tuition and giving students a monthly subsidy but students 
soon will have to start paying at least part of the cost 
some school authorities are beginning to realize the effect 
these changes can have on students and are providing counseling 
services 
the centers are also part of chinas changing attitude toward 
psychology and mental health 
during the ultraleftist 196676 cultural revolution all 
psychological work ceased and psychologists were told their field 
was unscientific 
now psychology has returned to most major universities and 
hospitals selfhelp mental health books are best sellers 
in 1986 an allchina youth mental health conference was 
convened and teachers and delegates agreed that psychological 
problems among college students was an area of concern chen said 
in this capital four schools including the prestigious beijing 
university have set up counseling centers at least 30 colleges 
and universities nationwide are providing similar services 
the counseling center at the beijing post and telecommunications 
college started in 1985 has treated 1224 students according to 
the englishlanguage newspaper china daily 
college students have many psychological problems which affect 
their studies said wang yan a specialist in childrens 
emotional disorders at beijing university china is just 
beginning to work on mental health and college students seem to 
have the greatest psychological problems 
one beijing university senior told a chinese newspaper that he 
feels just like a small boat sailing into the tempestuous sea 
with little psychological preparation 
some of the problems are not unusual or serious 
chen who heads the counseling center at beijing university 
said they rarely see serious cases of mental disorders in the 
students who come to the center inability of new students to 
adjust and relationship and romantic problems are most common 
however some extreme cases have been reported 
an 18yearold freshman at qinghua university chinas most 
prestigious technical school committed suicide last summer after 
failing an english exam 
liu yong a senior at beijing aviation college killed himself 
last summer after murdering a female classmate newspaper reports 
said he became emotionally unstable after reading the philosophies 
of jean paul sartre and nietzsche and the writing of french 
novelist emile zola 
the counseling centers provide a muchneeded service chen said 
but he was critical of their use of what he called common sense 
psychology 
many of the centers are staffed with wellmeaning teachers or 
other school personnel who have little training in psychology he 
said 
by contrast the clinic at beijing university is made up of four 
people from the psychology department 
a session with one of the psychologists costs 2 yuan 54 cents 
when the center opened two years ago treatment was free and four 
to five students came every day however financial concerns forced 
the professors to begin charging for their services this year 
chen calls their treatment method collective meaning that 
they use all methods and schools of psychology including freudian 
psychotherapy 
we use whatever is suitable for the patient he said 
</TEXT>
