<DOCNO> AP880711-0193 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
frank sciremammano gets seasick and has 
more stories about getting stuck in airports than getting stuck at 
sea 
so it may seem surprising that nasa has given him more than 
100000 in grants the past two years to study the antarctic ocean 
sciremammano a professor at rochester institute of technology 
has only actually seen the antarctic twice but he believes he 
knows as much about it as anyone thanks to satellites and 
computers 
satellite oceanography is still in its infancy but more and 
more people are getting interested he said when i got started 
in 1984 there were really only two or three groups involved 
now there are textbooks on the subject and seminars held to 
discuss new developments in the field that involves sophisticated 
radar measurements taken by satellite to study a wide range of 
information about the oceans behavior 
sciremammano says satellites can revolutionize some aspects of 
oceanography because scientists will no longer be limited to bits 
and pieces of data 
the satellites provide a global picture that traditional 
methods cant he said you can put instruments in the water 
and get a lot of wonderful information but only about that 
particular point 
thats especially important in a place like the antarctic ocean 
where a dearth of shipping activity makes dropping off measuring 
devices expensive and timeconsuming studying the antarctic the 
traditional way convinced sciremammano that satellites were the way 
to go 
we spent millions of dollars over years a lot of time and 
effort on the part of a lot of people and we really got one 
data point he said one good picture but in a very limited 
geographic area 
so now sciremammano pores over charts and tables constantly 
checks his electronic mailbox and keeps stacks of computer disks in 
his office hes using onetenth of all of rits computer memory to 
store the data he gets from space 
he said his research which focuses on the nature of the 
circumpolar current which swirls around the continent of antartica 
could someday provide some definitions for the el nino an 
unexplained weather phenomenon that causes severe droughts and 
flooding on both sides of the pacific ocean and for the 
muchtalked about greenhouse effect 
were trying to get a whole budget for the earths heat 
balance he said everybody understands that heat comes in at 
the equator and goes out more or less at the poles but the exact 
mechanisms for that transfer are not understood 
sciremammano admits that his work he teaches mechanical 
engineering and his landlocked location make him somewhat of an 
oddball oceanographer 
that has its advantages people leave me alone i dont have 
colleagues coming down to tell me about their latest adventure 
he said but i do feel a little isolated sometimes 
</TEXT>
