<TEXT>
under the sunlit arch of a plastic 
greenhouse an artificial swamp of cattails and elephant grass 
sprouts from hydroponic troughs soaking sustenance from a citys 
sewage 
this could be the waste treatment plant of the future 
picture it a natural system that uses microbes and marsh plants 
to transform raw sewage into sparkling clean water unlike 
conventional sewage facilities which cost a fortune to run this 
one makes money it leaves no nasty sludge it creates energy its 
so pretty it can be used as a park 
were looking at a whole new generation of waste treatment 
thats cheaper and much more efficient than anything thats 
available now and produces useful resources said william 
jewell a cornell university agricultural engineer 
beside ithacas new 40 million conventional treatment plant 
which settles aerates and chemically treats about 5 million 
gallons a day jewell has set up a pilot model of his system with 
the capacity to purify 10000 gallons of sewage a day about what 
100 people would produce 
the demonstration is funded by the state energy office and the 
gas research institute a utilitysponsored group trying to find 
new sources of natural gas 
in jewells system raw sewage is partially cleaned in a tankful 
of bacteria then piped into long low troughs in a greenhouse 
where it provides a nutrient film on which plants thrive the 
plants are grown hydroponically with no soil their roots form a 
dense mat as they soak up the pollutants 
a bonus to jewells sewage plant is that methane sold as 
natural gas is produced by the firststage bacterial process more 
can be made by harvesting the plants and putting them through a 
digester using the same bacteria 
jewell figures a plant with the capacity to handle the sewage of 
10000 people could generate 400000 worth of methane a year he 
estimates that for a community of 10000 his system would cost 
less than 1 million to build compared to at least 5 million for 
a conventional plant 
these are the wastewater treatment system of the future for 
small towns especially since the federal grant money for sewage 
treatment has dried up in the last few years said bc 
wolverton at nasas national space technology laboratory in bay 
st louis miss 
wolvertons artificial marshes which use floating plants like 
water hyacinths or rooted ones like bulrushes have treated all the 
chemical waste and sewage from the national aeronautics and space 
administration lab for more than 12 years weve saved many 
millions of dollars by using these systems 
most of the systems that wolverton has designed are for towns of 
fewer than 3000 people but an experimental system in san diego 
using water hyacinths to make potable water from sewage is 
expected to handle a million gallons a day 
