frank sciremammano gets seasick and has 
more stories about getting stuck in airports than getting stuck at 
sea 
so it may seem surprising that nasa has given him more than 
100000 in grants the past two years to study the antarctic ocean 
sciremammano a professor at rochester institute of technology 
has only actually seen the antarctic twice but he believes he 
knows as much about it as anyone thanks to satellites and 
computers 
satellite oceanography is still in its infancy but more and 
more people are getting interested he said when i got started 
in 1984 there were really only two or three groups involved 
now there are textbooks on the subject and seminars to discuss 
new developments in the field that involves sophisticated radar 
measurements taken by satellite to study a wide range of 
information about the oceans behavior 
sciremammano says satellites can revolutionize some aspects of 
oceanography because scientists will no longer be limited to bits 
and pieces of data 
the satellites provide a global picture that traditional 
methods cant he said you can put instruments in the water 
and get a lot of wonderful information but only about that 
particular point 
so sciremammano pores over charts and tables checks his 
electronic mailbox and keeps stacks of computer disks in his office 
he said his research which focuses on the nature of the 
circumpolar current which swirls around the continent of antartica 
could someday provide some definitions for the el nino an 
unexplained weather phenomenon that causes severe droughts and 
flooding on both sides of the pacific ocean and for the 
muchtalked about greenhouse effect 
