<TEXT>
pessimism may be bad for your health a study 
suggests 
the study of 99 men found that those with a pessimistic outlook 
about unfortunate experiences around age 25 tended to have poorer 
physical health 20 to 35 years later 
the men had filled out questionnaires in 1946 that asked about 
difficult wartime experiences independent judges studied the 
causes they offered for bad events ranking them for stability 
such as its never going to go away rather than it was a 
onetime thing globality its going to ruin everything i 
do vs it has no bearing on my life and internality its 
me instead of its the heat in this place 
a pessimistic explanatory style ranks high on those three 
factors the researchers from the university of michigan dartmouth 
medical school and the university of pennsylvania said in 
describing study results in the july issue of the journal of 
personality and social psychology 
records from physical examinations showed that a pessimistic 
explanatory style best predicted poor health at age 45 with less 
reliable predictions at ages 50 55 and 60 
among the possible explanations are that people with a 
pessimistic style may fail to seek or follow medical advice or 
maybe they neglect basic health care in the first place 
researchers said 
the men were academically successful independent and healthy 
so results of the study may not apply to people in general they 
said 
