<TEXT>
reynolds metals co will close its 
grand rapids plant which produces auto bumper parts and other 
extruded products by the end of the year the company said monday 
the plant will begin phasing down operations immediately said 
c stephen thomas vice president and general manager of the 
reynolds extrusion division 
thomas said reynolds will work with state and local government 
agencies to help find new employment for the plants 275 hourly 
employees and 61 salaried employees 
it was unknown whether any of the grand rapids plant employees 
would be transferred to reynolds other extrusion plants in 
bellwood va louisville ky and torrance calif company 
spokeswoman lou anne nabhan said 
about 98 percent of the hourly employees and a large percentage 
of the salaried employees are vested in the companys pension plan 
and many are eligible for early retirement thomas said 
thomas said employees had agreed to wage and benefit reductions 
in recent years to cut operating costs 
yet after several years of effort to make the facility more 
competitive and to stem continuing operating losses here we have 
no alternative to todays action he said 
the age of the plant built by the federal government in world 
war ii leased to reynolds in 1946 and purchased by the company in 
1949 was cited as a major factor in its closing 
nabhan said it was not known when the first reductions in the 
work force would occur no decision had been made on disposition of 
the site buildings or equipment 
