cpc international inc said its 
profit jumped 45 percent in the second quarter from a year earlier 
boosted in part by growth in its consumer food and corn refining 
operations 
the food conglomerate said its secondquarter profit rose to 72 
million or 91 cents a share from 498 million or 61 cents a 
share in the second quarter of 1987 
the earnings gain occurred despite a decline in secondquarter 
revenue to 123 billion from 132 billion a year earlier 
in the first six months of the year cpc earned 130 million or 
164 a share up from 925 million or 113 a share in the same 
period last year revenue for the sixmonth period fell to 231 
billion from 252 billion in 1987 
the figures do not reflect a special gain of 126 million from a 
restructuring last year that included the sale of european 
operations and interests in asian companies 
the strength of european currencies against the dollar a lower 
debt burden and lower us tax rate contributed to the 
secondquarter earnings performance said chairman james r eiszner 
for the year 1988 we now expect that cpcs earnings per share 
will show an increase of 30 percent or more excluding the special 
gain in 1987 eiszner said 
the drought gripping the nations farm belt probably will not 
have a significant impact on earnings because more than half of 
cpcs revenue comes from operations in 47 foreign countries he 
said 
