apollo computer inc announced monday 
two new low to midrange workstations designed to enhance efforts 
to recapture its position in the business computer marketplace 
the two systems the series 4500 and series 3500 workstations 
give apollo a new product line with an upgraded computer chip that 
could seriously challenge industry leader sun microsystems corp of 
sunnyvale calif several analysts said 
apollo has been losing its market share for two years to sun and 
other manufacuturers of workstations powerful computers for single 
users 
the 3500 will be only the second workstation to offer a powerful 
computer chip developed by motorola of austin texas but analysts 
note the price for the 3500 is about half of the 15000 
workstation by hewlettpackard inc using the motorola chip 
the 19000 series 4500 which is nearly twice as powerful as 
the apollo series 4000 workstation introduced last year is so far 
the only system offering an extrafast motorola presently being 
tested according to apollo 
both the 3500 and 4500 systems are scheduled to be available in 
december the company announced monday 
in overthecounter trading apollo fell 12 cents a share to 
1075 on volume of 16 million shares 
this is the last piece of the puzzle said apollo 
spokeswoman donna ruane with the new low and midrange systems 
it sets us up for a period of new growth 
on march 1 apollo announced the 70000 domain series 10000 a 
highpowered workstation targeted for specialized technical 
customers ruane said sales have so far been slow on the 10000 
which is scheduled to be shipped later this year 
jennifer johnson an analyst at international data corp in 
framingham said apollos introduction of the motorola chip should 
make significant gains in its competition with sun 
yet johnson warned apollo may be too confident of increased 
sales 
the most significant aspect of the announcement is that they 
leapfroged sun with the motorola chip its a very good product 
line and apollo is being aggressive but they are keeping the price 
down planning to get high sales volume they might be getting a 
bit too over aggressive she said 
robert herwick of hambrecht amp quist in new york said the new 
products give apollo the strongest overall line since 1986 but it 
may take time to convince customers 
this is more than just another feeble attempt to catch up to 
sun said herwick weve probably seen the worst of the pain 
apollo will go through because of a lesscompetitive product line 
theres likely to be some recovery now 
